report-pothole-or-street-issue.md:
## Report an issue {#report-an-issue}

Report potholes, broken pavement, missing or damaged signs, sinkholes, or other street issues online through the city’s 311 portal or by calling 311. Provide the exact location (address or cross streets) and a brief description of the issue. You may receive a reference number to track the request—save it for follow-up. Reports help the city prioritize repairs and plan maintenance; high-traffic or hazardous areas may be addressed sooner.

For emergency hazards (e.g., large sinkhole, downed wires, flooding), call 911 or the appropriate emergency line. For non-emergency but urgent issues (e.g., debris blocking a lane), 311 can route your report for a quicker response.

## What to include {#what-to-include}

Include the street name, nearest address or cross streets, and the type of issue (pothole, crack, sinkhole, broken curb, missing sign, etc.). If it is safe to do so, a photo can help crews locate and assess the problem. For hazards that affect traffic or pedestrians (e.g., deep pothole in a travel lane, broken sidewalk), note that in the description so it can be prioritized. If you have seen the issue cause damage or near-accidents, you can mention that as well.

You do not need to give your name to submit a report, though some systems allow you to create an account to track your requests and receive status updates.

## Track repair status {#track-repair-status}

Use your reference number to check the status of your report online (e.g., in the 311 portal under “My Requests”) or by calling 311. Response times depend on severity, season, and workload. Critical hazards (e.g., large potholes on busy roads, sinkholes) may be addressed quickly, sometimes with a temporary patch followed by a permanent repair. Routine repairs may be scheduled in the next maintenance cycle or when crews are in the area. Weather can delay paving and other work.

If the issue is not addressed within the expected time frame, you can follow up with your reference number. If the condition worsens or causes an incident, you can submit a new report or add to the existing one, depending on how the system works in your city.

voter-registration.md:
## Register to vote {#register-to-vote}

You can register to vote online, by mail, or in person at your local election office or motor vehicle agency (e.g., DMV). You will need to provide your name, address, date of birth, and identification as required by your state. Many states also offer same-day registration at polling places on election day—check your state’s rules.

Online registration is available in most states: visit your state’s election website or the national voter registration portal (e.g., vote.gov) and follow the steps. You may need a state-issued ID or the last four digits of your Social Security number. If you register by mail, use the form provided by your state and mail it before the registration deadline. When you renew or update your driver’s license, you can often register or update your registration at the same time.

## Check your status {#check-your-status}

Use your state’s online voter lookup tool to confirm that you are registered and to see your polling place and sample ballot. You can also verify that your address and party affiliation (in states that use it for primaries) are correct and update them if needed. Checking before election day helps avoid surprises—for example, if your polling place has changed or you need to request an absentee ballot after a move.

## Absentee and mail-in voting {#absentee-and-mail-in-voting}

If you cannot vote in person, you may request an absentee or mail-in ballot. Deadlines and rules vary by state: some require a reason (e.g., travel, illness), others allow any voter to vote by mail. Request your ballot early and return it by the stated deadline. Postmarks and drop box locations may be subject to specific rules—some states require receipt by election day, not just postmark. Follow the instructions that come with your ballot (e.g., signature, witness, envelope) to ensure it is counted.

In-person early voting is also available in many states; check your state’s website for dates and locations.

## Frequently asked questions

{#frequently-asked-questions}

:::dropdown{title="When is the registration deadline?"}
Deadlines are set by each state and may be
:::

15–30 days before an election. Check your state or local election website for the exact date. Missing the deadline may mean you cannot vote in that election unless your state allows same-day registration.

:::dropdown{title="Do I need ID at the polls?"}
Many states require
:::

photo ID or other forms of identification. Your state’s election site will list what is accepted (e.g., driver’s license, passport, tribal ID). Some states allow alternatives such as a utility bill or signed affidavit if you do not have ID. Check before you go.

:::dropdown{title="I moved. Do I need to re-register?"}

:::

Yes. Update your registration whenever you change your address so your ballot and polling place are correct. You can usually update online or when you get a new driver’s license. If you moved close to the deadline, check whether you can still vote at your old address or must vote by absentee ballot from your new address.

:::dropdown{title="I have a felony conviction. Can I vote?"}
Rules vary by state. Some states restore voting rights after completion of sentence (including parole); others have different rules. Check your state’s election website or a nonpartisan resource (e.g., Restore Your Vote) for current eligibility.
:::
